# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: atx
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The **16-pin 12VHPWR connector** is a standard for connecting graphics processing units (GPUs) to computer power supplies for up to 600 W power delivery.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] It was introduced by Nvidia in 2022 to supersede the previous 6- and 8-pin power connectors for GPUs.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The stated aim was to cater to the increasing power requirements of Nvidia GPUs.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The connector was formally adopted as part of PCI Express 5.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The connector was replaced by a minor revision called **12V-2x6**, introduced in 2023 with PCIe CEM 5.1 and PCIe ECN 6.0, which changed the GPU- and PSU-side sockets to ensure that the sense pins only make contact if the power pins are seated properly.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The cables and their plugs remained unchanged.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The change is intended to prevent melting due to partial contact, but melting continued to be reported for GPUs with this new socket.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] There is a significant change in power negotiation with a new sense pin added.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] 12VHPWR connectors are marked with an "H+" symbol, whereas 12V-2x6 connectors are marked with an "H++" symbol.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The connector first appeared in the Nvidia RTX 40 GPUs.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The 16-pin 12VHPWR connector, where "12V" signifies the use of 12 volts and "HPWR" stands for "high power", supports higher power delivery to GPUs, up to 600 watts, a significant increase from the 150 watts of the 8-pin connector and the 75 watts of the 6-pin connector.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The 16-pin connector comprises twelve power pins arranged in two parallel rows, and four auxiliary sense pins that communicate the maximum allowable power draw.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The plug housing should be colored black and made out of glass fibre-filled thermoplastic meeting the UL 94 V-0 classification for flame retardancy.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The pins should be made out of copper alloy with tin-plated contact areas.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] Adapters converting multiple 8-pin to a single 16-pin connector are available.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] With respect to power supplies, the 12VHPWR connector was first specified in the ATX12V 3.0 specification, where it was specified as required for PSUs over 450 W and optional for lower-wattage PSUs.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The above table describes the behavior of sense pins on 12VHPWR and 12V-2x6.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] There is an add-on Engineering Change Notice (ECN) to PCIe CEM 5.0 describing a requirement for the computer PSU to handle *power excursion*, short-term peak loads that exceed the stated maximum (sustained) permitted power on the connector.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] A power supply must be able to handle a 100-microsecond power draw at 3× of maximum sustained power.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] A similar change has been incorporated into PCIe CEM 5.1 for all add-in card power connectors.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The ECN is part of ATX 3.0 and PCIe CEM 5.1 is part of ATX 3.1.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] Some buyers of the Nvidia RTX 4090, the first GPU to use the new connector, reported that the connectors of their RTX 4090 were melting, which sparked several theories to explain it.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] After investigation, several sources reported that the main cause was the 12VHPWR connector not being fully seated while being put under load that resulted in overheating of the connector's pins, which in turn caused the melting of the plastic housing.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] PCI-SIG, the standards organization responsible for the creation of the 12VHPWR connector, has decided to make changes to the connector's specifications following the failures.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] A class-action lawsuit has been filed against Nvidia over melting 12VHPWR cables which the lawsuit states is "a dangerous product that should not have been sold in its current state".
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The plaintiff who brought the suit claims that Nvidia unjustly enriched itself, violated the product's warranty and engaged in fraud and they are demanding that Nvidia pay damages to affected customers as compensation.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] However, this lawsuit was voluntarily dismissed with prejudice by the plaintiff on March 10, 2023.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] No reason is provided as to why the case was dismissed.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] Following its own investigation and testing, Nvidia officially offered a statement on the melting connectors.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] They determined that the melting connectors are caused by user error from not inserting the 12VHPWR connector properly, causing partial contact.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] They have offered an expedited RMA process for any RTX 4090 affected by the melting connectors.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] PCI-SIG later said in a statement that Nvidia and their partners were still responsible for testing their products to account for user error.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] A revised connector design intended to address these issues was introduced under the new name 12V-2x6.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] Consumer Product Safety Commission announced a voluntary recall of 12VHPWR adapters made by Cablemod.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] According to the recall filing, 272 reports were filed with about 25,300 units shipped.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The recall covers adapters using both the initial and the revised 12V-2x6 (CEM 5.1) design.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] It was also reported that the new connectors have a limited lifespan of around 30–40 mating cycles before contact potentially becoming unreliable.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] For the entire connector with all applicable pins loaded at 12 V.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The old 8-pin power connector only uses three pins each for ground and 12 V.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] For this calculation the nominal voltage is used instead of considering the ATX 2.0/3.0 tolerance band.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The GeForce RTX 50 series use the new 12V-2x6 socket instead of the 12VHPWR.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] However, the high end RTX 5090 graphics card continued to show melting issues.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] These flaws are currently only confirmed on the RTX 5090 FE, but the removal of shunt resistors means the new re-design of the Nvidia cards exposes all cards to this flaw.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] Asus cards and some other brands add additional shunt resistors to detect potential overheating and warn the user, but without the ability to dynamically current balance and prevent overheating.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] Analysis of hardware design of the flagship Nvidia GPUs of the last few generations showed a crucial change.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The earlier GPU models with 6- or 8-pin power connectors usually had a separate current sensor per each connector.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] It allowed the GPU to monitor whether the load is distributed evenly among the connectors.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The Nvidia RTX 30 series achieved the same by splitting the six 12V pins of the 12VHPWR connector into three groups and also monitor them independently.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] Starting from the Nvidia RTX 40 series, all the 12V pins of the 12VHPWR connector are internally tied together, so the GPU does not know whether all the pins are making good contact.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] In this case, it is possible that the GPU may try to sink a lot of current through as little as a single pin, which would lead to excessive heat generation and melted connectors and wires as the result.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] Although the official reference design for the AMD Radeon RX 9070 XT uses traditional 8-pin sockets, a few manufacuters have opted for the new 12V-2x6 socket on their video cards incorporating this chip.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] In August 2025, an ASRock Taichi OC Radeon RX 9070 XT was reported as having a partly molten "12VHPWR" (actually 12V-2x6) connector on Reddit.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The GPU in question did not stop functioning, but discoloration could be seen on one of the power pins.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The port on the GPU side was connected via a 3×8-pin connector cable to the PSU.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] In response to the reliability concerns with these connectors, vendors have marketed several new features in related products, which attempt to improve safety when using these connectors.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] MSI and ASRock market high-power cables with connectors that use brightly-colored plastic around the metal contacts, with the goal of making improper connections more visually obvious.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] When completely inserted, none of the brightly-colored plastic should be visible.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] Regardless, there have been a couple of user reports of burnt, neon-yellow, MSI high-power connectors.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The same ASRock cable also has an NTC thermistor built into the GPU-end male connector.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] Temperature information from that sensor is transmitted to a special separate connector on the PSU end of the cable, which can then be connected to compatible ASRock PSUs.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] Such PSUs can then apply overheating protection based on the GPU connector's temperature.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] Certain ASUS RTX graphics cards include shunt resistors which allow ASUS software to detect amperage imbalances among the high-power pins.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The software can then alert the user if a significant imbalance is detected.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] Certain ZOTAC graphics cards will illuminate a red indicator LED and refuse to power on if they detect that the 12V-2x6 connector is not fully seated.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] The cards also use gold-plated pins in their 12V-2x6 connectors, reportedly for better conductivity and more resistance to corrosion.
[src:atx/16-pin-12vhpwr-connector] Similarly, certain Galax cards equipped with addressable RGB lighting will turn their lights yellow upon detection of an improper high-power connection.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] The **2011 Chengdu Foxconn explosion** occurred on May 13, 2011 in Chengdu, Sichuan province, People's Republic of China.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] The Foxconn factory (鸿富锦成都厂) where the incident took place is located at Pi County Hongguang (红光镇) with a total of about 52 production lines.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] In 2010 chairman Terry Gou referred to this area as the "Chengdu speed"(成都速度), a new development hub that Foxconn would centralise and turn Chengdu into the PRC's number one investment destination within five years.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] The explosive fire broke out at around 7:30pm and was quickly controlled by 10:00pm.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] At the time of the incident there were at least a couple hundred workers at the factory.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] After the explosion, more than 10 fire trucks and a large number of police showed up on the scene.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] The explosion occurred at the north factory A5 zone iPad 2 assembly line.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] A total of 3 people were killed with 15 injured.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] Singtao reported the explosion cause is related to either a furnace explosion or magnesium power related.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] The New York Times reported the root cause as a buildup of combustible aluminum dust.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] Numerous sources have said the explosion impact affected and cracked the factory building's 2nd, 3rd and 4th floor walls.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] However, Hon Hai spokesman Edmund Ding (丁祈安) said the explosion was only confined to a single workshop on one floor.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] The factory is an aluminum casing finishing (polishing) plant, and provides services for Apple, Microsoft, and Samsung among others, including work on the iPad line.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] Reports from the period following the explosions indicated that there would be expected slowdowns in production of the iPad 2 and many other devices.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] Foxconn denied that there would be any supply chain impact.
[src:atx/2011-chengdu-foxconn-explosion] The events caused Apple to have worker welfare concerns, and it began corporate and vendor governance changes to improve conditions at Chinese factories.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Certification is acquirable for products that have more than 80% energy efficiency at 20%, 50% and 100% of rated load, and a power factor of 0.9 or greater at 100% load.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] The Climate Savers Computing Initiative efficiency level targets for workstations for 2007 through 2011, corresponding to the 80 Plus certification levels.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] From July 2007 through June 2008, the basic 80 Plus level (Energy Star 4.0).
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] For the next year, the target is 80 Plus Bronze level, the following year 80 Plus Silver, then 80 Plus Gold, and finally Platinum.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] For the higher certification levels, the requirement of 0.9 or better power factor was extended to apply to 20% and 50% load levels, as well as at 100% load.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] The Platinum level requires 0.95 or better power factor for servers.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Redundancy is typically used in data centers.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Plug Load Solutions tests PSUs according to their testing protocol and lists certified PSUs with downloadable certificates in PDF format, allowing consumers to verify how many and which models are listed by each company.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] There have been instances where companies claim or imply that their supplies are 80 Plus when they have not been certified, and in some cases do not meet the requirements.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] For example, the highest 80 Plus is 80+ Titanium (95.4% efficiency at 50% load).
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Some companies will claim they meet this requirement even when they are only close (i.e.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] 94.xx%) therefore claiming 80+ Titanium.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] However, this is not the case as one could easily modify the test unit to be more enhanced than production models in order to slightly raise numbers.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] When a company resells an OEM power supply under a new name, it must be certified under the new name and company, even if the OEM supply is certified.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] In some instances, a reseller has claimed a higher wattage than the supply can deliver, so the resellers' supply would not meet 80 Plus requirements.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Although some power supply manufacturers name their products with similar names, such as "85 Plus", "90 Plus" and "95 Plus", there is no such official certification or standard.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] The efficiency of a computer power supply is its output power divided by its input power; the remaining input power is converted to heat as expected under conservation of energy.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] For instance, a 600 W power supply with 60% efficiency running at full load would draw 1000 W from the mains and waste 400 W as heat.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] A 600 W power supply with 80% efficiency running at full load would draw 750 W from the mains and waste only 150 W as heat.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] For a given power supply, efficiency varies depending on how much power is being delivered.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Supplies are typically most efficient at between half and three-quarters load, much less efficient at low load, and somewhat less efficient at maximum load.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Older ATX power supplies were typically 60% to 75% efficient.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] To qualify for 80 Plus, a power supply must achieve at least 80% efficiency at three specified loads (20%, 50% and 100% of maximum rated power).
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] However, 80 Plus supplies may still be less than 80% efficient at lower loads.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] For instance, an 80 Plus, 520 watt supply could still be 70% or less efficient at 60 watts (a typical idle power for a desktop computer).
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Thus it is still important to select a supply with capacity appropriate to the device being powered.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] It is easier to achieve the higher efficiency levels for higher wattage supplies, so gold and platinum supplies may be less available in consumer-level supplies of reasonable capacity for typical desktop machines.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Typical computer power supplies may have power factors as low as 0.5 to 0.6.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] The higher power factor reduces the peak current draw, reducing load on the circuit or on an uninterruptible power supply.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Reducing the heat output of the computer helps reduce noise, since fans do not have to spin as fast to cool the computer.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Reduced heat and resulting in lower cooling demands may increase computer reliability.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] The testing conditions may give an unrealistic expectation of efficiency for heavily loaded, high power (rated much larger than 300 W) supplies.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] A heavily loaded power supply and the computer it is powering generate significant amounts of heat, which may raise the power supply temperature, which is likely to decrease its efficiency.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Since power supplies are certified at room temperature, this effect is not taken into account.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Technically speaking, 80 Plus does test the power supply at full load, under which it is affected by its own heat generation.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] What it does *not* test is the effects of the heat generated by other components in the computer making its way into the power supply.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] There are additional requirements on testing PSUs with cooling fans, which draw power and reduce the measured efficiency.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] PSUs with no fan or an always-on, fixed-speed fan can be tested directly.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] PSUs with an internally-controlled fan must undergo a warmup period of 30 minutes or five fan cycles.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] PSUs with an externally-controlled fan should be tested at minimum fan speed setting.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] 80 Plus does not set efficiency targets for very low load.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] For instance, generation of standby power may still be relatively inefficient, and may not meet requirements of the One Watt Initiative.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Testing of 80 Plus power supplies shows that they vary considerably in standby efficiency.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] Some power supplies consume half a watt or less in standby with no load, where others consume several times as much at standby, even though they may meet higher 80 Plus certification requirement levels.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] The 80 Plus Titanium level expands requirements to include efficiency at 10% load.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] The 80 Plus Ruby level additionally includes efficiency at 5% load.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] See tables above for precise requirements.
[src:atx/80-plus-bronze] The 80 Plus measurement protocol includes the measurement of standby power, but it is not stated anywhere on their webpage whether it is taken account into certification.
[src:atx/amd-p01] AMD's main products include microprocessors, embedded processors, and graphics processors for servers, workstations, PCs, and embedded system applications, as well as chipsets for motherboards.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The company has also expanded into new markets, such as data centers, gaming, and high-performance computing.
[src:atx/amd-p01] AMD's processors are used in a wide range of computing devices, including PCs, servers, laptops, and gaming consoles.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Initially manufacturing its own processors, the company outsourced its manufacturing after GlobalFoundries was spun off in 2009.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Through its Xilinx acquisition in 2022, AMD offers field-programmable gate array (FPGA) products.
[src:atx/amd-p01] AMD was founded in 1969 by Jerry Sanders and a group of his fellow Fairchild Semiconductor colleagues.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The company's early products were primarily memory chips and other computer components.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In 1975, AMD entered the microprocessor market, competing with Intel, its main rival in the industry.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In the early 2000s, it experienced significant growth and success, partly due to its strong position in the PC market and its Athlon and Opteron processors.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The company faced challenges in the late 2000s and early 2010s, as it struggled to compete with Intel.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In the late 2010s, AMD regained market share by pursuing a penetration pricing strategy for its Ryzen processors, offering a competitive performance and lower costs than Intel microprocessors.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In 2022, AMD surpassed Intel by market capitalization for the first time.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Advanced Micro Devices was formally incorporated by Jerry Sanders, along with seven of his colleagues from Fairchild Semiconductor—Ed Turney; John Carey; Sven Simonsen; Jack Gifford, and three members of his team: Frank Botte, Jim Giles, and Larry Stenger, on May 1, 1969.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Sanders, an electrical engineer who was the director of marketing at Fairchild, had, like many of its executives, grown frustrated with the increasing lack of support, opportunity, and flexibility within the company.
[src:atx/amd-p01] He later decided to leave to start his own semiconductor company, following the footsteps of Robert Noyce (developer of the first silicon integrated circuit at Fairchild in 1959) and Gordon Moore, who together founded the semiconductor company Intel in July 1968.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In September 1969, AMD moved from its temporary location in Santa Clara to its new $500,000 15,000sqft headquarters at 901 Thompson Place, Sunnyvale, which housed the entire company, including the 8-mask, 7 μm feature size, 2-inch diameter wafer production.
[src:atx/amd-p01] To immediately secure a customer base, AMD initially became a second source supplier of microchips designed by Fairchild (the 5 V TTL "9300" logic series) and National Semiconductor.
[src:atx/amd-p01] AMD first focused on producing logic chips.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In November 1969, the company manufactured its first product: the Am9300, a 4-bit MSI shift register, which began selling in 1970.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Also in 1970, AMD produced its first proprietary product, the Am2501 logic counter, which was highly successful.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Its bestselling product in 1971 was the Am2505, the fastest multiplier available.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In 1971, AMD entered the RAM chip market, beginning with the Am3101, a 64-bit bipolar RAM.
[src:atx/amd-p01] That year AMD also greatly increased the sales volume of its linear integrated circuits, and by year-end the company's total annual sales reached US$4.6 million.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The company was a second source for Intel MOS/LSI circuits by 1973, with products such as Am14/1506 and Am14/1507, dual 100-bit dynamic shift registers.
[src:atx/amd-p01] By 1975, AMD was producing 212 products – of which 49 were proprietary, including the Am9102 (a static N-channel 1024-bit RAM) and three low-power Schottky MSI circuits: Am25LS07, Am25LS08, and Am25LS09.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Intel had created the first microprocessor, its 4-bit 4004, in 1971.
[src:atx/amd-p01] By 1975, AMD entered the microprocessor market with the Am9080, a reverse-engineered clone of the Intel 8080, and the Am2900 bit-slice microprocessor family.
[src:atx/amd-p01] When Intel began installing microcode in its microprocessors in 1976, it entered into a cross-licensing agreement with AMD, which was granted a copyright license to the microcode in its microprocessors and peripherals, effective October 1976.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In 1977, AMD entered into a joint venture with Siemens, a German engineering conglomerate wishing to enhance its technology expertise and enter the American market.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Siemens purchased 20% of AMD's stock, giving the company an infusion of cash to increase its product lines.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The two companies also jointly established Advanced Micro Computers (AMC), located in Silicon Valley and in Germany, allowing AMD to enter the microcomputer development and manufacturing field, in particular based on AMD's second-source Zilog Z8000 microprocessors.
[src:atx/amd-p01] When the two companies' vision for Advanced Micro Computers diverged, AMD bought out Siemens' stake in the American division in 1979.
[src:atx/amd-p01] AMD closed Advanced Micro Computers in late 1981 after switching focus to manufacturing second-source Intel x86 microprocessors.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Total sales in fiscal year 1978 topped $100 million, and in 1979, AMD debuted on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In 1979, production also began on AMD's new semiconductor fabrication plant in Austin, Texas; the company already had overseas assembly facilities in Penang and Manila, and began construction on a fabrication plant in San Antonio in 1981.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In 1980, AMD began supplying semiconductor products for telecommunications, an industry undergoing rapid expansion and innovation.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Intel had introduced the first x86 microprocessors in 1978.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In 1981, IBM created its personal computer, and wanted Intel's x86 processors, but only under the condition that Intel would also provide a second-source manufacturer for its patented x86 microprocessors.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Intel and AMD entered into a 10-year technology exchange agreement, first signed in October 1981 and formally executed in February 1982.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The technical information and licenses needed to make and sell a part would be exchanged for a royalty to the developing company.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The 1982 agreement also extended the 1976 AMD–Intel cross-licensing agreement through 1995.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The agreement included the right to invoke arbitration of disagreements, and after five years the right of either party to end the agreement with one year's notice.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The main result of the 1982 agreement was that AMD became a second-source manufacturer of Intel's x86 microprocessors and related chips, and Intel provided AMD with database tapes for its 8086, 80186, and 80286 chips.
[src:atx/amd-p01] However, in the event of a bankruptcy or takeover of AMD, the cross-licensing agreement would be effectively canceled.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Beginning in 1982, AMD began volume-producing second-source Intel-licensed 8086, 8088, 80186, and 80188 processors, and by 1984, its own Am286 clone of Intel's 80286 processor, for the rapidly growing market of IBM PCs and IBM clones.
[src:atx/amd-p01] It also continued its successful concentration on proprietary bipolar chips.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The company continued to spend greatly on research and development, and created the world's first 512K EPROM in 1984.
[src:atx/amd-p01] That year, AMD was listed in the book *The 100 Best Companies to Work for in America*, and later made the *Fortune* 500 list for the first time in 1985.
[src:atx/amd-p01] By mid-1985, the microchip market experienced a severe downturn, mainly due to long-term aggressive trade practices (dumping) from Japan, but also due to a crowded and non-innovative chip market in the United States.
[src:atx/amd-p01] During this time, AMD withdrew from the DRAM market, and made some headway into the CMOS market, which it had lagged in entering, having focused instead on bipolar chips.
[src:atx/amd-p01] AMD had some success in the mid-1980s with the AMD7910 and AMD7911 "World Chip" FSK modem, one of the first multi-standard devices that covered both Bell and CCITT tones at up to 1200 baud half duplex or 300/300 full duplex.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Beginning in 1986, AMD embraced the perceived shift toward RISC with its own AMD Am29000 (29k) processor; the 29k survived as an embedded processor.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The company also increased its EPROM memory market share in the late 1980s.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Throughout the 1980s, AMD was a second-source supplier of Intel x86 processors.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In 1991, it introduced its 386-compatible Am386, an AMD-designed chip.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Creating its own chips, AMD began to compete directly with Intel.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In January 1996, AMD acquired NexGen for $857 million to develop what eventually became AMD K6.
[src:atx/amd-p01] At the time, NexGen was working on its Nx686 microprocessor.
[src:atx/amd-p01] AMD had a large, successful flash memory business, even during the dotcom bust.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In December 2005, AMD divested itself of Spansion to focus on the microprocessor market, and Spansion went public in an IPO.
[src:atx/amd-p01] On July 24, 2006, AMD announced its acquisition of the Canadian 3D graphics card company ATI Technologies.
[src:atx/amd-p01] AMD paid $4.3 billion and 58 million shares of its capital stock, for approximately $5.4 billion.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The transaction was completed on October 25, 2006.
[src:atx/amd-p01] On August 30, 2010, AMD announced that it would retire the ATI brand name for its graphics chipsets in favor of the AMD brand name.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In October 2008, AMD announced plans to spin off manufacturing operations in the form of GlobalFoundries Inc., a multibillion-dollar joint venture with Advanced Technology Investment Co., an investment company formed by the government of Abu Dhabi.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The partnership and spin-off gave AMD an infusion of cash and allowed it to focus solely on chip design.
[src:atx/amd-p01] To assure the Abu Dhabi investors of the new venture's success, AMD's CEO Hector Ruiz stepped down in July 2008, while remaining executive chairman, in preparation for becoming chairman of GlobalFoundries in March 2009.
[src:atx/amd-p01] President and COO Dirk Meyer became AMD's CEO.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Recessionary losses necessitated AMD cutting 1,100 jobs in 2009.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In August 2011, AMD announced that former Lenovo executive Rory Read would be joining the company as CEO, replacing Meyer.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In November 2011, AMD announced plans to lay off more than 10% (1,400) of its employees from across all divisions worldwide.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In October 2012, it announced plans to lay off an additional 15% of its workforce to reduce costs in the face of declining sales revenue.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The inclusion of AMD chips into the PlayStation 4 and Xbox One were later seen as saving AMD from bankruptcy.
[src:atx/amd-p01] AMD acquired the low-power server manufacturer SeaMicro in early 2012, with an eye to bringing out an Arm64 server chip.
[src:atx/amd-p01] On October 8, 2014, AMD announced that Rory Read had stepped down after three years as president and chief executive officer.
[src:atx/amd-p01] He was succeeded by Lisa Su, a key lieutenant who had been chief operating officer since June.
[src:atx/amd-p01] On October 16, 2014, AMD announced a new restructuring plan along with its Q3 results.
[src:atx/amd-p01] As part of this restructuring, AMD announced that 7% of its global workforce would be laid off by the end of 2014.
[src:atx/amd-p01] After the GlobalFoundries spin-off and subsequent layoffs, AMD was left with significant vacant space at 1 AMD Place, its aging Sunnyvale headquarters office complex.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In August 2016, AMD's 47 years in Sunnyvale came to a close when it signed a lease with the Irvine Company for a new 220,000 sq. ft. headquarters building in Santa Clara.
[src:atx/amd-p01] AMD's new location at Santa Clara Square faces the headquarters of arch-rival Intel across the Bayshore Freeway and San Tomas Aquino Creek.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Around the same time, AMD also agreed to sell 1 AMD Place to the Irvine Company.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In April 2019, the Irvine Company secured approval from the Sunnyvale City Council of its plans to demolish 1 AMD Place and redevelop the entire 32-acre site into townhomes and apartments.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In October 2020, AMD announced that it was acquiring Xilinx, the market leader in field programmable gate arrays and complex programmable logic devices (FPGAs and CPLDs) in an all-stock transaction.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The acquisition was completed in February 2022, with an estimated acquisition price of $50 billion.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In January 2024, AMD announced it was discontinuing the production of all complex programmable logic devices (CPLDs) acquired through Xilinx.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In March 2024, a rally in semiconductor stocks pushed AMD's valuation above $300B for the first time.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In July 2024, AMD announced that it would acquire the Finnish-based artificial intelligence start-up company Silo AI in a $665 million all-cash deal in an attempt to better compete with AI chip market leader Nvidia.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In August 2024, AMD signed a deal to acquire ZT Systems for $4.9 billion.
[src:atx/amd-p01] The company creates custom computing infrastructure that is used for AI tasks.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Since early 2024, AMD has made significant gains in the server CPU market, reducing the gap with Intel.
[src:atx/amd-p01] Initial reports of a 50:50 market split drew on incorrect data and were later revised.
[src:atx/amd-p01] As of July 2025, Intel holds 63.3% of the server CPU market, while AMD has reached 36.5%, showing a strong upward trend for AMD despite Intel's continuing lead.
[src:atx/amd-p01] In June 2025, AMD unveiled the AI server for 2026, the MI400 series of chips, which will be the basis of a new server called "Helios".
[src:atx/amd-p01] In October 2025, the company announced it had agreed a deal with OpenAI to sell six gigawatts of its AI processors over the next five years.
[src:atx/amd-p01] As part of the deal, OpenAI has the option to acquire a 10 per cent stake in AMD: 160 million shares at a token price of $0.01 per share contingent on meeting undisclosed performance targets, the final tranche of options requiring AMD common stock to reach $600 per share.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In February 1982, AMD signed a contract with Intel, becoming a licensed second-source manufacturer of 8086 and 8088 processors.
[src:atx/amd-p02] IBM wanted to use the Intel 8088 in its IBM PC, but its policy at the time was to require at least two sources for its chips.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD later produced the Am286 under the same arrangement.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 1984, Intel internally decided to no longer cooperate with AMD in supplying product information to shore up its advantage in the marketplace, and delayed and eventually refused to convey the technical details of the Intel 80386.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 1987, AMD invoked arbitration over the issue, and Intel reacted by canceling the 1982 technological-exchange agreement altogether.
[src:atx/amd-p02] After three years of testimony, AMD eventually won in arbitration in 1992, but Intel disputed this decision.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Another long legal dispute followed, ending in 1994 when the Supreme Court of California sided with the arbitrator and AMD.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 1990, Intel countersued AMD, renegotiating AMD's right to use derivatives of Intel's microcode for its cloned processors.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In the face of uncertainty during the legal dispute, AMD was forced to develop clean room designed versions of Intel code for its x386 and x486 processors, the former long after Intel had released its own x386 in 1985.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In March 1991, AMD released the Am386, its clone of the Intel 386 processor.
[src:atx/amd-p02] By October of the same year it had sold one million units.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 1993, AMD introduced the first of the Am486 family of processors, which proved popular with a large number of original equipment manufacturers, including Compaq, which signed an exclusive agreement using the Am486.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Am5x86, another Am486-based processor, was released in November 1995, and continued AMD's success as a fast, cost-effective processor.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Finally, in an agreement effective 1996, AMD received the rights to the microcode in Intel's x386 and x486 processor families, but not the rights to the microcode in the following generations of processors.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD's first in-house x86 processor was the K5, launched in 1996.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The "K" in its name was a reference to Kryptonite, the only substance known to harm comic book character Superman.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This itself was a reference to Intel's hegemony over the market, i.e., an anthropomorphization of them as Superman.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The number "5" was a reference to the fifth generation of x86 processors; rival Intel had previously introduced its line of fifth-generation x86 processors as Pentium because the U.S.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Trademark and Patent Office had ruled that mere numbers could not be trademarked.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 1996, AMD purchased NexGen, specifically for the rights to its Nx series of x86-compatible processors.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD gave the NexGen design team their own building, left them alone, and gave them time and money to rework the Nx686.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The result was the K6 processor, introduced in 1997.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Although it was based on Socket 7, variants such as K6-III/450 were faster than Intel's Pentium II (sixth-generation processor).
[src:atx/amd-p02] The K7 was AMD's seventh-generation x86 processor, making its debut under the brand name Athlon on June 23, 1999.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Unlike previous AMD processors, it could not be used on the same motherboards as Intel's, due to licensing issues surrounding Intel's Slot 1 connector, and instead used a Slot A connector, referenced to the Alpha processor bus.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Duron was a lower-cost and limited version of the Athlon (64 KB instead of 256 KB L2 cache) in a 462-pin socketed PGA (socket A) or soldered directly onto the motherboard.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Sempron was released as a lower-cost Athlon XP, replacing Duron in the socket A PGA era.
[src:atx/amd-p02] It has since been migrated upward to all new sockets, up to AM3.
[src:atx/amd-p02] On October 9, 2001, the Athlon XP was released.
[src:atx/amd-p02] On February 10, 2003, the Athlon XP with 512 KB L2 Cache was released.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The technology was initially launched as the Opteron server-oriented processor on April 22, 2003.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Shortly thereafter, it was incorporated into a product for desktop PCs, branded Athlon 64.
[src:atx/amd-p02] On April 21, 2005, AMD released the first dual-core Opteron, an x86-based server CPU.
[src:atx/amd-p02] A month later, it released the Athlon 64 X2, the first desktop-based dual-core processor family.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In May 2007, AMD abandoned the string "64" in its dual-core desktop product branding, becoming Athlon X2, downplaying the significance of 64-bit computing in its processors.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Further updates involved improvements to the microarchitecture, and a shift of the target market from mainstream desktop systems to value dual-core desktop systems.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 2008, AMD started to release dual-core Sempron processors exclusively in China, branded as the Sempron 2000 series, with lower HyperTransport speed and smaller L2 cache.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD completed its dual-core product portfolio for each market segment.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In September 2007, AMD released the first server Opteron K10 processors, followed in November by the Phenom processor for desktop.
[src:atx/amd-p02] K10 processors came in dual-core, triple-core, and quad-core versions, with all cores on a single die.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD released a new platform codenamed "Spider", which used the new Phenom processor, and an R770 GPU and a 790 GX/FX chipset from the AMD 700 chipset series.
[src:atx/amd-p02] However, AMD built the Spider at 65nm, which was uncompetitive with Intel's smaller and more power-efficient 45nm.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In January 2009, AMD released a new processor line dubbed Phenom II, a refresh of the original Phenom built using the 45 nm process.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD's new platform, codenamed "Dragon", used the new Phenom II processor, and an ATI R770 GPU from the R700 GPU family, and a 790 GX/FX chipset from the AMD 700 chipset series.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Phenom II came in dual-core, triple-core and quad-core variants, all using the same die, with cores disabled for the triple-core and dual-core versions.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Phenom II resolved issues that the original Phenom had, including a low clock speed, a small L3 cache, and a Cool'n'Quiet bug that decreased performance.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Phenom II cost less but was not performance-competitive with Intel's mid-to-high-range Core 2 Quads.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Phenom II also enhanced its predecessor's memory controller, allowing it to use DDR3 in a new native socket AM3, while maintaining backward compatibility with AM2+, the socket used for the Phenom, and allowing the use of the DDR2 memory that was used with the platform.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In April 2010, AMD released a new Phenom II Hexa-core (6-core) processor codenamed "Thuban".
[src:atx/amd-p02] This was a totally new die based on the hexa-core "Istanbul" Opteron processor.
[src:atx/amd-p02] It included AMD's "turbo core" technology, which allows the processor to automatically switch from 6 cores to 3 faster cores when more pure speed is needed.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Magny Cours and Lisbon server parts were released in 2010.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Magny Cours part came in 8 to 12 cores and the Lisbon part in 4 and 6 core parts.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Magny Cours is focused on performance while the Lisbon part is focused on high performance per watt.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Magny Cours is an MCM (multi-chip module) with two hexa-core "Istanbul" Opteron parts.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This will use a new socket G34 for dual and quad-socket processors and thus will be marketed as Opteron 61xx series processors.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Lisbon uses socket C32 certified for dual-socket use or single socket use only and thus will be marketed as Opteron 41xx processors.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Both will be built on a 45 nm SOI process.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The initiative intended to move some of the processing originally done on the CPU (e.g. floating-point unit operations) to the GPU, which is better optimized for some calculations.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Fusion was later renamed the AMD APU (Accelerated Processing Unit).
[src:atx/amd-p02] Llano was AMD's first APU built for laptops.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Llano was the second APU released, targeted at the mainstream market.
[src:atx/amd-p02] It incorporated a CPU and GPU on the same die, and northbridge functions, and used "Socket FM1" with DDR3 memory.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The CPU part of the processor was based on the Phenom II "Deneb" processor.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD suffered an unexpected decrease in revenue based on production problems for the Llano.
[src:atx/amd-p02] More AMD APUs for laptops running Windows 7 and Windows 8 OS are being used commonly.
[src:atx/amd-p02] These include AMD's price-point APUs, the E1 and E2, and their mainstream competitors with Intel's Core i-series: The Vision A- series, the A standing for accelerated.
[src:atx/amd-p02] These range from the lower-performance A4 chipset to the A6, A8, and A10.
[src:atx/amd-p02] These all incorporate next-generation Radeon graphics cards, with the A4 utilizing the base Radeon HD chip and the rest using a Radeon R4 graphics card, with the exception of the highest-model A10 (A10-7300) which uses an R6 graphics card.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Bulldozer was AMD's microarchitecture codename for server and desktop AMD FX processors, first released on October 12, 2011.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This family 15h microarchitecture is the successor to the family 10h (K10) microarchitecture design.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Bulldozer was a clean-sheet design, not a development of earlier processors.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The core was specifically aimed at 10–125 W TDP computing products.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD claimed dramatic performance-per-watt efficiency improvements in high-performance computing (HPC) applications with Bulldozer cores.
[src:atx/amd-p02] While hopes were high that Bulldozer would bring AMD to be performance-competitive with Intel once more, most benchmarks were disappointing.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In some cases the new Bulldozer products were slower than the K10 models they were built to replace.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Piledriver microarchitecture was the 2012 successor to Bulldozer, increasing clock speeds and performance relative to its predecessor.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Piledriver would be released in AMD FX, APU, and Opteron product lines.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Piledriver was subsequently followed by the Steamroller microarchitecture in 2013.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Used exclusively in AMD's APUs, Steamroller focused on greater parallelism.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 2015, the Excavator microarchitecture replaced Piledriver.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Expected to be the last microarchitecture of the Bulldozer series, Excavator focused on improved power efficiency.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Bobcat microarchitecture was revealed during a speech from Henri Richard, AMD executive vice-president, in Computex 2007, and was put into production during the first quarter of 2011.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Based on the difficulty competing in the x86 market with a single core optimized for the 10–100 W range, AMD had developed a simpler core with a target range of 1–10 watts.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In addition, it was believed that the core could migrate into the hand-held space if the power consumption can be reduced to less than 1 W.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Jaguar is a microarchitecture codename for Bobcat's successor, released in 2013, that is used in various APUs from AMD aimed at the low-power/low-cost market.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Jaguar and its derivates would go on to be used in the custom APUs of the PlayStation 4, Xbox One, PlayStation 4 Pro, Xbox One S, and Xbox One X.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Jaguar would be later followed by the Puma microarchitecture in 2014.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 2012, AMD announced it was working on ARM products, both as a semi-custom product and server product.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The initial server product was announced as the Opteron A1100 in 2014, an 8-core Cortex-A57-based ARMv8-A SoC, and was expected to be followed by an APU incorporating a Graphics Core Next GPU.
[src:atx/amd-p02] However, the Opteron A1100 was not released until 2016, with the delay attributed to adding software support.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The A1100 was also criticized for not having support from major vendors upon its release.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 2014, AMD also announced the K12 custom core for release in 2016.
[src:atx/amd-p02] While being ARMv8-A instruction set architecture compliant, the K12 was expected to be entirely custom-designed, targeting the server, embedded, and semi-custom markets.
[src:atx/amd-p02] While ARM architecture development continued, products based on K12 were subsequently delayed with no release planned.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Development of AMD's x86-based Zen microarchitecture was preferred.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Zen is an architecture for x86-64 based Ryzen series of CPUs and APUs, introduced in 2017 by AMD and built from the ground up by a team led by Jim Keller, beginning with his arrival in 2012, and taping out before his departure in September 2015.
[src:atx/amd-p02] One of AMD's primary goals with Zen was an IPC increase of at least 40%, however in February 2017 AMD announced that it had actually achieved a 52% increase.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Processors made on the Zen architecture are built on the 14 nm FinFET node and have a renewed focus on single-core performance and HSA compatibility.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Previous processors from AMD were either built in the 32 nm process ("Bulldozer" and "Piledriver" CPUs) or the 28 nm process ("Steamroller" and "Excavator" APUs).
[src:atx/amd-p02] Because of this, Zen is much more energy efficient.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Zen architecture is the first to encompass CPUs and APUs from AMD built for a single socket (Socket AM4).
[src:atx/amd-p02] Also new for this architecture is the implementation of simultaneous multithreading (SMT) technology, something Intel has had for years on some of its processors with its proprietary hyper-threading implementation of SMT.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This is a departure from the "Clustered MultiThreading" design introduced with the Bulldozer architecture.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD released the Zen-based high-end Ryzen 7 "Summit Ridge" series CPUs on March 2, 2017, mid-range Ryzen 5 series CPUs on April 11, 2017, and entry level Ryzen 3 series CPUs on July 27, 2017.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD later released the Epyc line of Zen derived server processors for 1P and 2P systems.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In October 2017, AMD released Zen-based APUs as Ryzen Mobile, incorporating Vega graphics cores.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In January 2018, AMD announced its new lineup plans, with Ryzen 2.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD launched CPUs with the 12nm Zen+ microarchitecture in April 2018, following up with the 7nm Zen 2 microarchitecture in June 2019, including an update to the Epyc line with new processors using the Zen 2 microarchitecture in August 2019, and Zen 3 slated for release in Q3 2020.
[src:atx/amd-p02] As of 2019, AMD's Ryzen processors were reported to outsell Intel's consumer desktop processors.
[src:atx/amd-p02] At CES 2020 AMD announced its Ryzen Mobile 4000, as the first 7 nm x86 mobile processor, the first 7 nm 8-core (also 16-thread) high-performance mobile processor, and the first 8-core (also 16-thread) processor for ultrathin laptops.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This generation is still based on the Zen 2 architecture.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In October 2020, AMD announced new processors based on the Zen 3 architecture.
[src:atx/amd-p02] On PassMark's Single thread performance test the Ryzen 5 5600x bested all other CPUs besides the Ryzen 9 5950X.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In April 2020, AMD launched three new SKUs which target commercial HPC workloads & hyperconverged infrastructure applications.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The launch was based on Epyc's 7 nm second-generation Rome platform and supported by Dell EMC, Hewlett Packard Enterprise, Lenovo, Supermicro, and Nutanix.
[src:atx/amd-p02] IBM Cloud was its first public cloud partner.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In August 2022, AMD announced its initial lineup of CPUs based on the new Zen 4 architecture.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Steam Deck, PlayStation 5, Xbox Series X and Series S all use chips based on the Zen 2 microarchitecture, with proprietary tweaks and different configurations in each system's implementation than AMD sells in its own commercially available APUs.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Lee Ka Lau, Francis Lau, Benny Lau, and Kwok Yuen Ho founded ATI in 1985 as Array Technology Incorporated, renamed later Array Technologies Incorporated and finally ATI Technologies.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Working primarily in the OEM field, ATI produced integrated graphics cards for PC manufacturers such as IBM and Commodore.
[src:atx/amd-p02] By 1987, ATI had grown into an independent graphics-card retailer, introducing EGA Wonder and VGA Wonder card product lines that year.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In the early nineties, they released products able to process graphics without the CPU: in May 1991, the Mach8, in 1992 the Mach32, which offered improved memory bandwidth and GUI acceleration.
[src:atx/amd-p02] ATI Technologies went public in 1993, with shares listed on NASDAQ and on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 1994, the Mach64 accelerator debuted, powering the Graphics Xpression and Graphics Pro Turbo, offering hardware support for YUV-to-RGB colour space conversion in addition to hardware zoom; early techniques of hardware-based video acceleration.
[src:atx/amd-p02] ATI introduced its first combination of 2D and 3D accelerator under the name 3D Rage.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This chip was based on the Mach 64, but it featured elemental 3D acceleration.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The ATI Rage line powered almost the entire range of ATI graphics products.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In particular, the Rage Pro was one of the first viable 2D-plus-3D alternatives to 3dfx's 3D-only Voodoo chipset.
[src:atx/amd-p02] 3D acceleration in the Rage line advanced from the basic functionality within the initial 3D Rage to a more advanced DirectX 6.0 accelerator in 1999 Rage 128.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The All-in-Wonder product line, introduced in 1996, was the first combination of integrated graphics chip with TV tuner card and the first chip that enabled display of computer graphics on a TV set.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The cards featured 3D acceleration powered by ATI's 3D Rage II, 64-bit 2D performance, TV-quality video acceleration, analogue video capture, TV tuner functionality, flicker-free TV-out and stereo TV audio reception.
[src:atx/amd-p02] ATI entered the mobile computing sector by introducing 3D-graphics acceleration to laptops in 1996.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Mobility product line had to meet requirements different from those of desktop PCs, such as minimized power usage, reduced heat output, TMDS output capabilities for laptop screens, and maximized integration.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 1997, ATI acquired Tseng Labs's graphics assets, which included 40 engineers.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Radeon line of graphics products was unveiled in 2000.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The initial Radeon GPU offered an all-new design with DirectX 7.0 3D acceleration, video acceleration, and 2D acceleration.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Technology developed for a specific Radeon generation could be built in varying levels of features and performance in order to provide products suited for the entire market range, from high-end to budget to mobile versions.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 2000, ATI acquired ArtX, which engineered the Flipper graphics chip used in the GameCube video game console.
[src:atx/amd-p02] They also created a modified version of the chip (codenamed Hollywood) for the successor of the GameCube, the Wii.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Microsoft contracted ATI to design the graphics core (codenamed Xenos) for the Xbox 360.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Later in 2005, ATI acquired Terayon's cable modem silicon intellectual property, strengthening their lead in the consumer digital television market.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Ho remained as chairman of the board until he retired in November 2005.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Dave Orton replaced him as the president and CEO of the organization.
[src:atx/amd-p02] On July 24, 2006, a joint announcement revealed that AMD would acquire ATI in a deal valued at $5.6 billion.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The acquisition consideration closed on October 25, 2006, and included over $2 billion financed from a loan and 56 million shares of AMD stock.
[src:atx/amd-p02] ATI's operations became part of the AMD Graphics Product Group (GPG), and ATI's CEO Dave Orton became the executive vice president of Visual and Media Businesses at AMD until his resignation in 2007.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The top-level management was reorganized with the senior vice president and general manager, and the senior vice president and general manager of Consumer Electronics Group, both of whom would report to the CEO of AMD.
[src:atx/amd-p02] On August 30, 2010, John Trikola announced that AMD would retire the ATI brand for its graphics chipsets in favour of the AMD name.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 2007, the ATI division of AMD released the TeraScale microarchitecture implementing a unified shader model.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This design replaced the previous fixed-function hardware of previous graphics cards with multipurpose, programmable shaders.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Initially released as part of the GPU for the Xbox 360, this technology would go on to be used in Radeon branded HD 2000 parts.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Three generations of TeraScale would be designed and used in parts from 2007 to 2015.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In a 2009 restructuring, AMD merged the CPU and GPU divisions to support the company's APUs, which fused both graphics and general purpose processing.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 2011, AMD released the successor to TeraScale, Graphics Core Next (GCN).
[src:atx/amd-p02] This new microarchitecture emphasized GPGPU compute capability in addition to graphics processing, with a particular aim of supporting heterogeneous computing on AMD's APUs.
[src:atx/amd-p02] GCN's reduced instruction set ISA allowed for significantly increased compute capability over TeraScale's very long instruction word ISA.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Since GCN's introduction with the HD 7970, five generations of the GCN architecture have been produced from 2011 through at least 2018.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In September 2015, AMD separated the graphics technology division of the company into an independent internal unit called the Radeon Technologies Group (RTG), headed by Raja Koduri.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This gave the graphics division of AMD autonomy in product design and marketing.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The RTG then went on to create and release the Polaris and Vega microarchitectures released in 2016 and 2017, respectively.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In particular the Vega, or fifth-generation GCN, microarchitecture includes a number of major revisions to improve performance and compute capabilities.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In November 2017, Raja Koduri left RTG and CEO and President Lisa Su took his position.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In January 2018, it was reported that two industry veterans joined RTG, namely Mike Rayfield as senior vice president and general manager of RTG, and David Wang as senior vice president of engineering for RTG.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In January 2020, AMD announced that its second-generation RDNA graphics architecture was in development, with the aim of competing with the Nvidia RTX graphics products for performance leadership.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In October 2020, AMD announced its new RX 6000 series series GPUs, their first high-end product based on RDNA2 and capable of handling ray-tracing natively, aiming to challenge Nvidia's RTX 3000 GPUs.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 2012, AMD's then CEO Rory Read began a program to offer semi-custom designs.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Rather than AMD simply designing and offering a single product, potential customers could work with AMD to design a custom chip based on AMD's intellectual property.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Customers pay a non-recurring engineering fee for design and development, and a purchase price for the resulting semi-custom products.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In particular, AMD noted its unique position of offering both x86 and graphics intellectual property.
[src:atx/amd-p02] These semi-custom designs would have design wins as the APUs in the PlayStation 4 and Xbox One and the subsequent PlayStation 4 Pro, Xbox One S, Xbox One X, Xbox Series X/S, and PlayStation 5.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Financially, these semi-custom products would represent a majority of the company's revenue in 2016.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In November 2017, AMD and Intel announced that Intel would market a product combining in a single package an Intel Core CPU, a semi-custom AMD Radeon GPU, and HBM2 memory.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Before the launch of Athlon 64 processors in 2003, AMD designed chipsets for its processors spanning the K6 and K7 processor generations.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The chipsets include the AMD-640, AMD-751, and the AMD-761 chipsets.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The situation changed in 2003 with the release of Athlon 64 processors, and AMD chose not to further design its own chipsets for its desktop processors while opening the desktop platform to allow other firms to design chipsets.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This was the "Open Platform Management Architecture" with ATI, VIA and SiS developing its own chipset for Athlon 64 processors and later Athlon 64 X2 and Athlon 64 FX processors, including the Quad FX platform chipset from Nvidia.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The initiative went further with the release of Opteron server processors as AMD stopped the design of server chipsets in 2004 after releasing the AMD-8111 chipset, and again opened the server platform for firms to develop chipsets for Opteron processors.
[src:atx/amd-p02] As of today, Nvidia and Broadcom are the sole designing firms of server chipsets for Opteron processors.
[src:atx/amd-p02] As the company completed the acquisition of ATI Technologies in 2006, the firm gained the ATI design team for chipsets which previously designed the Radeon Xpress 200 and the Radeon Xpress 3200 chipsets.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD then renamed the chipsets for AMD processors under AMD branding (for instance, the CrossFire Xpress 3200 chipset was renamed as AMD 580X CrossFire chipset).
[src:atx/amd-p02] In February 2007, AMD announced the first AMD-branded chipset since 2004 with the release of the AMD 690G chipset (previously under the development codename *RS690*), targeted at mainstream IGP computing.
[src:atx/amd-p02] It was the industry's first to implement a HDMI 1.2 port on motherboards, shipping for more than a million units.
[src:atx/amd-p02] While ATI had aimed at releasing an Intel IGP chipset, the plan was scrapped and the inventories of Radeon Xpress 1250 (codenamed *RS600*, sold under ATI brand) was sold to two OEMs, Abit and ASRock.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Although AMD stated the firm would still produce Intel chipsets, Intel had not granted the license of 1333 MHz FSB to ATI.
[src:atx/amd-p02] On November 15, 2007, AMD announced a new chipset series portfolio, the AMD 7-Series chipsets, covering from the enthusiast multi-graphics segment to the value IGP segment, to replace the AMD 480/570/580 chipsets and AMD 690 series chipsets, marking AMD's first enthusiast multi-graphics chipset.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Discrete graphics chipsets were launched on November 15, 2007, as part of the codenamed *Spider* desktop platform, and IGP chipsets were launched at a later time in spring 2008 as part of the codenamed *Cartwheel* platform.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD returned to the server chipsets market with the AMD 800S series server chipsets.
[src:atx/amd-p02] It includes support for up to six SATA 6.0 Gbit/s ports, the C6 power state, which is featured in Fusion processors and AHCI 1.2 with SATA FIS-based switching support.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This is a chipset family supporting Phenom processors and Quad FX enthusiast platform (890FX), IGP (890GX).
[src:atx/amd-p02] With the advent of AMD's APUs in 2011, traditional northbridge features such as the connection to graphics and the PCI Express controller were incorporated into the APU die.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Accordingly, APUs were connected to a single chip chipset, renamed the Fusion Controller Hub (FCH), which primarily provided southbridge functionality.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD released new chipsets in 2017 to support the release of its new Ryzen products.
[src:atx/amd-p02] As the Zen microarchitecture already includes much of the northbridge connectivity, the AM4-based chipsets primarily varied in the number of additional PCI Express lanes, USB connections, and SATA connections available.
[src:atx/amd-p02] These AM4 chipsets were designed in conjunction with ASMedia.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In the early 1990s, AMD began marketing a series of embedded system-on-a-chips (SoCs) called AMD Élan, starting with the SC300 and SC310.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Both combines a 32-Bit, Am386SX, low-voltage 25 MHz or 33 MHz CPU with memory controller, PC/AT peripheral controllers, real-time clock, PLL clock generators and ISA bus interface.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The SC300 integrates in addition two PC card slots and a CGA-compatible LCD controller.
[src:atx/amd-p02] They were followed in 1996 by the SC4xx types, now supporting VESA Local Bus and using the Am486 with up to 100 MHz clock speed.
[src:atx/amd-p02] An SC450 at 33 MHz, for example, was used in the Nokia 9110 Communicator.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Using an Am586 with 100 MHz or 133 MHz and supporting SDRAM and PCI it was the latest member of the series.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In February 2002, AMD acquired Alchemy Semiconductor for its Alchemy line of MIPS processors for the hand-held and portable media player markets.
[src:atx/amd-p02] On June 13, 2006, AMD officially announced that the line was to be transferred to Raza Microelectronics, Inc., a designer of MIPS processors for embedded applications.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In August 2003, AMD also purchased the Geode business which was originally the Cyrix MediaGX from National Semiconductor to augment its existing line of embedded x86 processor products.
[src:atx/amd-p02] During the second quarter of 2004, it launched new low-power Geode NX processors based on the K7 Thoroughbred architecture with speeds of fanless processors 667 MHz and 1 GHz, and 1.4 GHz processor with fan, of TDP 25 W.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This technology is used in a variety of embedded systems (Casino slot machines and customer kiosks for instance), several UMPC designs in Asia markets, and the OLPC XO-1 computer, an inexpensive laptop computer intended to be distributed to children in developing countries around the world.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Geode LX processor was announced in 2005 and is said will continue to be available through 2015.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD has also introduced 64-bit processors into its embedded product line, starting with the AMD Opteron processor.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Leveraging the high throughput enabled through HyperTransport and the Direct Connect Architecture these server-class processors have been targeted at high-end telecom and storage applications.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 2007, AMD added the AMD Athlon, AMD Turion, and Mobile AMD Sempron processors to its embedded product line.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Leveraging the same 64-bit instruction set and Direct Connect Architecture as the AMD Opteron but at lower power levels, these processors were well suited to a variety of traditional embedded applications.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The ATI acquisition in 2006 included the Imageon and Xilleon product lines.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In late 2008, the entire handheld division was sold off to Qualcomm, who have since produced the Adreno series.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Also in 2008, the Xilleon division was sold to Broadcom.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In April 2007, AMD announced the release of the M690T integrated graphics chipset for embedded designs.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This enabled AMD to offer complete processor and chipset solutions targeted at embedded applications requiring high-performance 3D and video such as emerging digital signage, kiosk, and Point of Sale applications.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The M690T was followed by the M690E specifically for embedded applications which removed the TV output, which required Macrovision licensing for OEMs, and enabled native support for dual TMDS outputs, enabling dual independent DVI interfaces.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In January 2011, AMD announced the AMD Embedded G-Series Accelerated Processing Unit.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This was the first APU for embedded applications.
[src:atx/amd-p02] These were followed by updates in 2013 and 2016.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In May 2012, AMD announced the AMD Embedded R-Series Accelerated Processing Unit.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This family of products incorporates the Bulldozer CPU architecture, and Discrete-class Radeon HD 7000G Series graphics.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This was followed by a system-on-a-chip (SoC) version in 2015 which offered a faster CPU and faster graphics, with support for DDR4 SDRAM memory.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD builds graphic processors for use in embedded systems.
[src:atx/amd-p02] They can be found in anything from casinos to healthcare, with a large portion of products being used in industrial machines.
[src:atx/amd-p02] These products include a complete graphics processing device in a compact multi-chip module including RAM and the GPU.
[src:atx/amd-p02] ATI began offering embedded GPUs with the E2400 in 2008.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Since then, AMD has released regular updates to its embedded GPU lineup in 2009, 2011, 2015, and 2016; reflecting improvements in its GPU technology.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In October 2020, AMD announced its acquisition of Xilinx, which was completed on February 14, 2022, through an all-stock transaction valued at approximately $60 billion.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Xilinx remained a wholly owned subsidiary of AMD until the brand was phased out in June 2023, with Xilinx's product lines now branded under AMD.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 2011, AMD began selling Radeon branded DDR3 SDRAM to support the higher bandwidth needs of AMD's APUs.
[src:atx/amd-p02] While the RAM is sold by AMD, it was manufactured by Patriot Memory and VisionTek.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This was later followed by higher speeds of gaming oriented DDR3 memory in 2013.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Radeon branded DDR4 SDRAM memory was released in 2015, despite no AMD CPUs or APUs supporting DDR4 at the time.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD noted in 2017 that these products are "mostly distributed in Eastern Europe" and that it continues to be active in the business.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD announced in 2014 that it would sell Radeon branded solid-state drives manufactured by OCZ with capacities up to 480 GB and using the SATA interface.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD has taken actions towards opening its software tools above the firmware level in the past decade.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Software not explicitly stated as being free can be assumed to be proprietary.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD Radeon Software is the default channel for official software distribution from AMD.
[src:atx/amd-p02] It includes both free and proprietary software components, and supports both Microsoft Windows and Linux.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Most notable public AMD software is on the GPU side.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Previously, AMD produced its chips at company-owned semiconductor foundries.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD pursued a strategy of collaboration with other semiconductor manufacturers IBM and Motorola to co-develop production technologies.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD's founder Jerry Sanders termed this the "Virtual Gorilla" strategy to compete with Intel's significantly greater investments in fabrication.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Two former fabrication sites in Sunnyvale are listed as a Superfund site, added in 1986 and 1990 when volatile organic compounds were discovered in groundwater.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Acid neutralization system (ANS) tank vaults were discovered with holes when excavated with the contaminated soil.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 2008, AMD spun off its chip foundries into an independent company named GlobalFoundries.
[src:atx/amd-p02] This breakup of the company was attributed to the increasing costs of each process node.
[src:atx/amd-p02] The Emirate of Abu Dhabi purchased the newly created company through its subsidiary Advanced Technology Investment Company (ATIC), purchasing the final stake from AMD in 2009.
[src:atx/amd-p02] With the spin-off of its foundries, AMD became a fabless semiconductor manufacturer, designing products to be produced at for-hire foundries.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Part of the GlobalFoundries spin-off included an agreement with AMD to produce some number of products at GlobalFoundries.
[src:atx/amd-p02] Both prior to the spin-off and after, AMD has pursued production with other foundries including TSMC and Samsung.
[src:atx/amd-p02] It has been argued that this would reduce risk for AMD by decreasing dependence on any one foundry which has caused issues in the past.
[src:atx/amd-p02] In 2018, AMD started shifting the production of its CPUs and GPUs to TSMC, following GlobalFoundries' announcement that it was halting development of its 7 nm process.
[src:atx/amd-p02] AMD revised its wafer purchase requirement with GlobalFoundries in 2019, allowing AMD to freely choose foundries for 7 nm nodes and below, while maintaining purchase agreements for 12 nm and above through 2021.
[src:atx/amd-p03] AMD has a long history of litigation with former (and current) partner and x86 creator Intel.
[src:atx/amd-p03] AMD's sponsorship of Formula 1 racing began in 2002, and since 2020 has sponsored the Mercedes-AMG Petronas team.
[src:atx/amd-p03] AMD was also a sponsor of the BMW Sauber and Scuderia Ferrari Formula 1 teams together with Intel, Vodafone, AT&T, Pernod Ricard and Diageo.
[src:atx/amd-p03] On 18 April 2018, AMD began a multi-year sponsorship with Scuderia Ferrari.
[src:atx/amd-p03] In February 2020, just prior to the start of the 2020 race season, the Mercedes Formula 1 team announced it was adding AMD to its sponsorship portfolio.
[src:atx/amd-p03] AMD began a sponsorship deal with Victory Five (V5) for the League of Legends Pro League (LPL) in 2022.
[src:atx/amd-p03] AMD was a sponsor of the Chinese Dota Pro Circuit together with Perfect World.
[src:atx/amd-p03] In February 2024, AMD was a Diamond sponsor for the World Artificial Intelligence Cannes Festival (WAICF).
[src:atx/amd-p03] AMD was a Platinum sponsor for the HPE Discover 2024, an event hosted by Hewlett Packard Enterprise to showcase technology for government and business customers.
[src:atx/amd-p03] The event was held from 17 to 20 June 2024 in Las Vegas.
[src:atx/aopen] The company was incorporated in December 1996 as a subsidiary of Acer Group with an initial public offering (IPO) at the Taiwan stock exchange in August 2002.
[src:atx/aopen] It is also the first subsidiary that established the entrepreneurship paradigm in the pan-Acer Group.
[src:atx/aopen] At that time, AOpen's major shareholder was the Wistron Group.
[src:atx/aopen] In 2018, AOpen became a partner of the pan-Acer Group again as the business-to-business branch of the computing industry.
[src:atx/aopen] AOpen is perhaps most well known for their *mobile on desktop* (MoDT), which implements Intel's Pentium M platform on desktop motherboards.
[src:atx/aopen] Because the Pentium 4 and other NetBurst CPUs proved less energy efficient than the Pentium M, in late 2004 and early 2005, many manufacturers introduced desktop motherboards for the mobile Pentium M, AOpen being one of the first.
[src:atx/aopen] AOpen currently specializes in ultra small form factor (uSFF) platform applications; digital signage; and product development and designs characterized by miniaturization, standardization and modularization.
[src:atx/aopen] AOpen has developed energy-saving products since 2005.
[src:atx/aopen] According to different types of customers, applications and contexts, AOpen splits its product platforms into two major categories: media player platform and Panel PC platform, both of which have Windows, Linux, ChromeOS and Android devices.
[src:atx/atx] ATX is a commonly used motherboard and power supply hardware form factor for desktop computers.
[src:atx/atx] The ATX form factor defined a general mounting point placement and I/O panel size that smaller motherboards share (such as microATX, FlexATX, and Mini-ITX), making them backwards compatible in many computer cases.
[src:atx/atx] As of 2012, ATX is the most common motherboard design.
[src:atx/atx] Other standards for smaller boards (including microATX, FlexATX, nano-ITX, and mini-ITX) keep the basic rear layout but reduce the size of the board and the number of expansion slots.
[src:atx/atx] Dimensions of a full-size ATX board are 12 × 9.6 in (305 × 244 mm) which means microATX boards fit in many ATX chassis.
[src:atx/atx] The ATX specifications were patented by David Dent at Intel and co-developed with Astec America, a major manufacturer of power supplies at the time.
[src:atx/atx] The inaugural version 1.0 of the ATX specification was unveiled by Intel in July 1995.
[src:atx/atx] Since then, ATX has been revised numerous times.
[src:atx/atx] The most recent ATX motherboard specification is version 2.2.
[src:atx/atx] The most recent ATX12V power supply unit specification is ATX 3.0 released in February 2022.
[src:atx/atx] EATX, or E-ATX (Extended ATX), is a term that refers to motherboards larger than the ATX standard.
[src:atx/atx] Motherboards labeled E-ATX commonly share dimensions with the SSI-EEB (Server System Infrastructure - Enterprise Electronics Bay) standard (12 x 13 in), however, it is not a guarantee.
[src:atx/atx] While some dual-CPU-socket motherboards have been implemented in ATX, the extra size of EATX makes it the typical form factor for dual-socket systems and for single-socket systems with a large number of memory slots (or more than two memory channels).
[src:atx/atx] In 2004, Intel announced the BTX (Balanced Technology eXtended) standard, intended as a replacement for ATX.
[src:atx/atx] While some manufacturers adopted the new standard, Intel discontinued any future development of BTX in 2006.
[src:atx/atx] As of 2026, the ATX design still remains the standard for personal computers.
[src:atx/atx] On the back of the computer case, some major changes were made to the AT standard.
[src:atx/atx] Originally AT style cases had only a keyboard connector and expansion slots for add-on card backplates.
[src:atx/atx] Any other onboard interfaces (such as serial and parallel ports) had to be connected via flying leads to connectors which were mounted either on spaces provided by the case or brackets placed in unused expansion slot positions.
[src:atx/atx] The ATX standard specified a rectangular area on the back of the system where motherboard manufacturers can arrange ports any way they want.
[src:atx/atx] A number of general patterns (depending on which ports the motherboard offers) have been used by most manufacturers.
[src:atx/atx] Cases are usually fitted with a snap-out panel, also known as an I/O plate or I/O shield, in one of the common arrangements.
[src:atx/atx] I/O plates are usually included with retail motherboards for installation in any suitable case.
[src:atx/atx] The computer will operate correctly without a plate fitted, but there will be open gaps in the case which may compromise the EMI/RFI screening and allow the ingress of dirt and random foreign bodies.
[src:atx/atx] Panels were made that fit an AT motherboard in an ATX case.
[src:atx/atx] Some ATX motherboards come with an integrated I/O plate.
[src:atx/atx] ATX also made the PS/2-style mini-DIN keyboard and mouse connectors ubiquitous.
[src:atx/atx] AT systems used a 5-pin DIN connector for the keyboard and were generally used with serial port mice (although PS/2 mouse ports were also found on some systems).
[src:atx/atx] Many modern motherboards are phasing out the PS/2-style keyboard and mouse connectors in favor of the more modern Universal Serial Bus.
[src:atx/atx] Other legacy connectors that are slowly being phased out of modern ATX motherboards include 25-pin parallel ports and 9-pin RS-232 serial ports.
[src:atx/atx] In their place are onboard peripheral ports such as Ethernet, FireWire, eSATA, audio ports (both analog and S/PDIF), video (analog D-sub, DVI, HDMI, or DisplayPort), extra USB ports, and Wi-Fi.
[src:atx/atx] A notable issue with the ATX specification was that it was last revised when power supplies were normally placed at the top of many old computer cases rather than at the bottom, as with many modern computer cases.
[src:atx/atx] This has led to some problematic standard locations for ports, in particular the 4/8 pin CPU power, which is normally located along the top edge of the board, convenient for top-mounted power supplies.
[src:atx/atx] This makes it very difficult for cables from bottom-mounted power supplies to reach, and commonly requires a special cutout in the back plane for the cable to come in from behind and bend around the board, making insertion and wire management very difficult.
[src:atx/atx] Many power supply cables barely or fail to reach, or are too stiff to make the bend, and extensions are sometimes required due to this placement.
[src:atx/atx] Modern power supplies often have longer cables to alleviate this issue.
[src:atx/atx] Several ATX-derived designs have been specified that use the same power supply, mountings and basic back panel arrangement, but set different standards for the size of the board and number of expansion slots.
[src:atx/atx] Standard ATX provides seven slots at 0.8 in (20 mm) spacing; the popular microATX size removes 2.4 inches (61 mm) and three slots, leaving four.
[src:atx/atx] Here width refers to the distance along the external connector edge, while depth is from front to rear.
[src:atx/atx] Note each larger size inherits all previous (smaller) colors area.
[src:atx/atx] AOpen has conflated the term Mini ATX with a more recent 15 × 15 cm (5.9 × 5.9 in) design.
[src:atx/atx] Since references to Mini ATX have been removed from ATX specifications since the adoption of microATX, the AOpen definition is the more contemporary term and the one listed above is apparently only of historical significance.
[src:atx/atx] This sounds contradictory to the now common Mini-ITX standard (17 × 17 cm (6.7 × 6.7 in)), which is a potential source of confusion.
[src:atx/atx] A number of manufacturers have added one to three additional expansion slots (at the standard 0.8 inch spacing) to the standard 12-inch ATX motherboard width.
[src:atx/atx] Form factors considered obsolete in 1999 included Baby-AT, full size AT, and the semi-proprietary LPX for low-profile cases.
[src:atx/atx] Proprietary motherboard designs such as those by Compaq, Packard-Bell, Hewlett Packard and others existed, and were not interchangeable with multi-manufacturer boards and cases.
[src:atx/atx] Portable and notebook computers and some 19-inch rackmount servers have custom motherboards unique to their particular products.
[src:atx/atx] While E-ATX and SSI EEB (Server System Infrastructure (SSI) Forum's Enterprise Electronics Bay (EEB)) share the same dimensions, the screw holes of the two standards do not all align; rendering them incompatible.
[src:atx/atx] In 2008, Foxconn unveiled a Foxconn F1 motherboard prototype, which has the same width as a standard ATX motherboard, but an extended 14.4" length to accommodate 10 slots.
[src:atx/atx] The firm called the new 14.4 × 9.6 in (366 × 244 mm) design of this motherboard "Ultra ATX" in its CES 2008 showing.
[src:atx/atx] Also unveiled during the January 2008 CES was the Lian Li Armorsuit PC-P80 case with 10 slots designed for the motherboard.
[src:atx/atx] In 2010, EVGA Corporation released a new motherboard, the "Super Record 2", or SR-2, whose size surpasses that of the "EVGA X58 Classified 4-Way SLI".
[src:atx/atx] The new board is designed to accommodate two Dual QPI LGA1366 socket CPUs (e.g.
[src:atx/atx] Intel Xeon), similar to that of the Intel Skulltrail motherboard that could accommodate two Intel Core 2 Quad processors and has a total of seven PCI-E slots and 12 DDR3 RAM slots.
[src:atx/atx] The ATX specification requires the power supply to produce three main outputs, +3.3 V, +5 V and +12 V.
[src:atx/atx] Low-power −12 V and +5 VSB (standby) supplies are also required.
[src:atx/atx] The −12 V supply is primarily used to provide the negative supply voltage for RS-232 ports and is also used by one pin on conventional PCI slots primarily to provide a reference voltage for some models of sound cards.
[src:atx/atx] The 5 VSB supply is used to produce trickle power to provide the soft-power feature of ATX when a PC is turned off, as well as powering the real-time clock to conserve the charge of the CMOS battery.
[src:atx/atx] A −5 V output was originally required because it was supplied on the ISA bus.
[src:atx/atx] However, it was removed in later versions of the ATX standard once ISA expansion slots became obsolete.
[src:atx/atx] Originally, the motherboard was powered by one 20-pin connector.
[src:atx/atx] An ATX power supply provides a number of peripheral power connectors and (in modern systems) two connectors for the motherboard: an 8-pin (or 4+4-pin) auxiliary connector providing additional power to the CPU and a main 24-pin power supply connector, an extension of the original 20-pin version.
[src:atx/atx] The connector pin pitch is 4.20 mm (about one sixth of an inch).
[src:atx/atx] Generally, supply voltages must be within ±5% of their nominal values at all times.
[src:atx/atx] The little-used negative supply voltages, however, have a ±10% tolerance.
[src:atx/atx] The 20–24-pin Molex Mini-Fit Jr. has a power rating of, 9 amperes maximum per pin).
[src:atx/atx] As large server motherboards and 3D graphics cards have required progressively more and more power to operate, it has been necessary to revise and extend the standard beyond the original 20-pin connector, to allow more current using multiple additional pins in parallel.
[src:atx/atx] The low circuit voltage is the restriction on power flow through each connector pin; at the maximum rated voltage, a single Mini-Fit Jr pin would be capable of 4800 watts.
[src:atx/atx] That last dimension, the 140 mm depth, is frequently varied, with depths of 160, 180, 200 and 230 mm used to accommodate higher power, larger fan and/or modular connectors.
[src:atx/atx] Original AT cases (flat case style) have an integrated power switch that protruded from the power supply and sits flush with a hole in the AT chassis.
[src:atx/atx] It utilizes a paddle-style DPST switch and is similar to the PC and PC-XT style power supplies.
[src:atx/atx] Later AT (so-called "Baby AT") and LPX style computer cases have a power button that is directly connected to the system computer power supply (PSU).
[src:atx/atx] The general configuration is a double-pole latching mains voltage switch with the four pins connected to wires from a four-core cable.
[src:atx/atx] The wires are either soldered to the power button (making it difficult to replace the power supply if it failed) or blade receptacles were used.
[src:atx/atx] An ATX power supply is typically controlled by an electronic switch connected to the power button on the computer case and allows the computer to be turned off by the operating system.
[src:atx/atx] In addition, many ATX power supplies have a manual switch on the back that also ensures no power is being sent to the components.
[src:atx/atx] When the switch on the power supply is turned off, the computer cannot be turned on with the front power button.
[src:atx/atx] ATX uses one large, keyed connector which can not be connected incorrectly.
[src:atx/atx] The new connector also provides a 3.3 volt source, removing the need for motherboards to derive this voltage from the 5 V rail.
[src:atx/atx] Some motherboards, particularly those manufactured after the introduction of ATX but whilst LPX equipment was still in use, support both LPX and ATX PSUs.
[src:atx/atx] A minimum load on one or more voltages may be required (varies by model and vendor); the standard does not specify operation without a minimum load and a conforming PSU may shut down, output incorrect voltages, or otherwise malfunction, but will not be hazardous or damaged.
[src:atx/atx] An ATX power supply is not a replacement for a current-limited bench laboratory DC power supply; instead it is better described as a bulk DC power supply.
[src:atx/atx] The original ATX specification called for a power supply to be located near to the CPU with the power supply fan drawing in cooling air from outside the chassis and directing it onto the processor.
[src:atx/atx] It was thought that in this configuration, cooling of the processor would be achievable without the need of an active heatsink.
[src:atx/atx] This recommendation was removed from later specifications; modern ATX power supplies usually exhaust air from the case.
[src:atx/atx] The power distribution specification defined that most of the PSU's power should be provided on 5 V and 3.3 V rails, because most of the electronic components (CPU, RAM, chipset, PCI, AGP and ISA cards) used 5 V or 3.3 V for power supply.
[src:atx/atx] While designing the Pentium 4 platform in 1999/2000, the standard 20-pin ATX power connector was found insufficient to meet increasing power-line requirements; the standard was significantly revised into ATX12V 1.0 (ATX12V 1.x is sometimes inaccurately called ATX-P4).
[src:atx/atx] ATX12V 1.x was also adopted by AMD Athlon XP and Athlon 64 systems.
[src:atx/atx] However, some early model Athlon XP and MP boards (including some server boards) and later model lower-end motherboards do not have the 4-pin connector as described below.
[src:atx/atx] Numbering of the ATX revisions may be a little confusing: ATX refers to the design, and goes up to version 2.2 in 2004 (with the 24 pins of ATX12V 2.0), while ATX12V describes only the PSU.
[src:atx/atx] For instance, ATX 2.03 is quite commonly seen on PSUs from 2000 and 2001 and often includes the P4 12V connector, even if the norm itself did not define it yet.
[src:atx/atx] Formally called the *+12 V Power Connector*, this is commonly referred to as the **P4 connector** because this was first needed to support the Pentium 4 processor.
[src:atx/atx] Before the Pentium 4, processors were generally powered from the 5 V rail.
[src:atx/atx] Later processors operate at much lower voltages, typically around 1 V and some draw over 100 A.
[src:atx/atx] It is infeasible to provide power at such low voltages and high currents from a standard system power supply, so the Pentium 4 established the practice of generating it with a DC-to-DC converter on the motherboard next to the processor, powered by the 4-pin 12 V connector.
[src:atx/atx] This is a minor revision from August 2000.
[src:atx/atx] The power on the 3.3 V rail was slightly increased and other smaller changes were made.
[src:atx/atx] A relatively minor revision from January 2002.
[src:atx/atx] The only significant change was that the −5 V rail was no longer required (it became optional).
[src:atx/atx] This voltage was required by the ISA bus, which is no longer present on almost all modern computers.
[src:atx/atx] Introduced in April 2003 (a month after 2.0).
[src:atx/atx] This standard introduced some changes, mostly minor.
[src:atx/atx] ATX12V 2.x brought a significant design change regarding power distribution.
[src:atx/atx] By analyzing the power demands of then-current PCs, it was determined that it would be much cheaper and more practical to power most PC components from 12 V rails, instead of from 3.3 V and 5 V rails.
[src:atx/atx] In particular, PCI Express expansion cards take much of their power from the 12 V rail (up to 5.5 A), while the older AGP graphics cards took only up to 1 A on 12 V and up to 6 A on 3.3 V.
[src:atx/atx] The CPU is also driven by a 12 V rail, while it was done by a 5 V rail on older PCs (before the Pentium 4).
[src:atx/atx] This is a minor revision from June 2004.
[src:atx/atx] An errant reference for the −5 V rail was removed.
[src:atx/atx] This is a minor revision from March 2005.
[src:atx/atx] The power was slightly increased on all rails.
[src:atx/atx] Efficiency requirements changed: minimum 65% at light load, 72% at typical load, and 70% at full load.
[src:atx/atx] Introduced recommended minimum values of 75% at light load, 80% at typical load, and 77% at full load.
[src:atx/atx] Also released in March 2005 it includes corrections and specifies High Current Series wire terminals for 24-pin ATX motherboard and 4-pin +12 V power connectors.
[src:atx/atx] Recommended efficiency was increased to 80% (with at least 70% required) and the 12 V minimum load requirement was lowered.
[src:atx/atx] Higher efficiency generally results in less power consumption (and less waste heat) and the 80% recommendation brings supplies in line with new Energy Star 4.0 mandates.
[src:atx/atx] The reduced load requirement allows compatibility with processors that draw very little power during startup.
[src:atx/atx] The absolute over-current limit of 240 VA per rail was removed, allowing 12 V lines to provide more than 20 A per rail.
[src:atx/atx] This revision became effective in February 2008.
[src:atx/atx] The ATX12V 2.4 specifications were published in August 2012.
[src:atx/atx] It is specified in Revision 1.31 of the *Power Supply Design Guide for Desktop Platform Form Factors*, which names this as ATX12V version 2.4.
[src:atx/atx] In July 2012, revision 1.3 of the *Power Supply Design Guide for Desktop Platform Form Factors* made inclusion of the floppy drive connector optional, instead of mandatory.
[src:atx/atx] The specifications for ATXV12 2.51 were released in September 2021 and introduced support for *Alternative Low Power Mode (ALPM)* which supersedes the traditional S3 power state.
[src:atx/atx] Windows 10 implements this functionality as *Modern Standby*.
[src:atx/atx] Power supply fans are also recommended to turn on with at least a two second delay for an improved user experience.
[src:atx/atx] This version also stated that the floppy drive connector should be excluded from PSUs, as opposed to merely being optional, and marked that connector's section in the specification as "For Historical Reference Only".
[src:atx/atx] The specifications for ATX12V 2.53 were released in December 2021 and constitute another minor update to the ATX standard.
[src:atx/atx] ATX12V 2.53 makes further recommendations on efficiency and references the Energy Star *Computers Specification Version 8.0* which was finalized in April 2020.
[src:atx/atx] The specifications for ATX 3.0 were released in February 2022.
[src:atx/atx] It includes the new 16-pin 12VHPWR connector that can deliver up to 600 W for H+ and up to 675 W in H++ to graphics cards.
[src:atx/atx] These incorporate data lines for components to negotiate power capabilities with the PSU so they do not draw more power than the PSU is capable of delivering.
[src:atx/atx] The specification also has more strict requirements for handling spikes, two times the nominal output for 100 microseconds.
[src:atx/atx] The −12 V supply is now specified as optional on the ATX motherboard connector, and some PSU manufacturers (e.g.
[src:atx/atx] Corsair) have begun removing the −12 V supply from their PSUs.
[src:atx/atx] However, as of 2025, some motherboards (e.g. recent designs from ASRock) still use the −12 V supply - typically to power the amplifier for on-board audio - and functions that use it will not work as expected when paired with a PSU that does not provide a −12 V supply.
[src:atx/atx] ATX 3.1 replaces the 12VHPWR power connector with the 12V-2x6 power connector and reduces required power loss hold-up time from 17 milliseconds to 12 milliseconds.
[src:atx/atx] Standing for **ATX 12-volt-only**, this is a new specification published by Intel in 2019, aimed at pre-built systems in the first run, and stricter power efficiency requirements by the California Energy Commission going into effect in 2021.
[src:atx/atx] Several OEMs were already using a similar design with proprietary connectors and this effectively standardizes those.
[src:atx/atx] Under this standard, power supplies provide only a 12 V output.
[src:atx/atx] ATX12VO introduces a new 10-pin connector to supply the motherboard, replacing the 24-pin ATX12V connector.
[src:atx/atx] This greatly simplifies power supplies, but moves DC-to-DC conversion and some connectors to the motherboard instead.
[src:atx/atx] Notably, SATA power connectors, which include 3.3 V and 5 V pins, need to move to the motherboard instead of being connected directly to the power supply.
[src:atx/atx] Connector pinout per Intel ATX12VO (12V Only) Desktop Power Supply Design Guide.
[src:atx/atx] SFX (Small Form-Factor eXtended) is merely a design for a small form factor (SFF) power supply casing (such as those using microATX, FlexATX, nano-ITX, mini-ITX, and NLX), with the power specifications almost identical to ATX.
[src:atx/atx] Thus, an SFX power supply is mostly pin-compatible with the ATX power supply as the main difference is its reduced dimensions; the only electrical difference is that the SFX specifications do not require the −5 V rail.
[src:atx/atx] Since −5 V is required only by some ISA-bus expansion cards, this is not an issue with modern hardware and decreases productions costs.
[src:atx/atx] As a result, ATX pin 20, which carried −5 V, is absent in current power supplies; it was optional in ATX and ATX12V version 1.2 and deleted as of ATX version 1.3.
[src:atx/atx] SFX has dimensions of 125 × 63.5 × 100 mm (width × height × depth), with a 60 mm fan, compared with the standard ATX dimensions of 150 × 86 × 140 mm.
[src:atx/atx] Optional 80 or 40 mm fan replacement increases or decreases the height of an SFX unit.
[src:atx/atx] Some manufacturers and retailers incorrectly market SFX power supplies as μATX or MicroATX power supplies.
[src:atx/atx] Some manufacturers make SFX-L dimensions of 125 × 63.5 × 130 mm to accommodate a 120 mm fan.
[src:atx/atx] Thin Form Factor is another small power supply design with standard ATX specification connectors.
[src:atx/atx] WTX power supplies provide a WTX style motherboard connector which is incompatible with the standard ATX motherboard connector.
[src:atx/atx] This is an ATX12V power supply derivative made by AMD to power its Athlon MP (dual processor) platform.
[src:atx/atx] It was used only on high-end Athlon MP motherboards.
[src:atx/atx] It has a special 8-pin supplemental connector for motherboard, so an AMD GES PSU is required for such motherboards (those motherboards will not work with ATX(12 V) PSUs).
[src:atx/atx] ATX12V-GES 24-pin P1 motherboard connector.
[src:atx/atx] ATX12V-GES 8-pin P2 motherboard connector.
[src:atx/atx] EPS12V is defined in Server System Infrastructure (SSI) and used primarily by SMP/multi-core systems such as Core 2, Core i7, Opteron and Xeon.
[src:atx/atx] It has a 24-pin ATX motherboard connector (same as ATX12V v2.x), an 8-pin secondary connector and an optional 4-pin tertiary connector.
[src:atx/atx] Rather than include the extra cable, many power supply makers implement the 8-pin connector as two combinable 4-pin connectors to ensure backwards compatibility with ATX12V motherboards.
[src:atx/atx] High-performance video card power demands dramatically increased during the 2000s and some high-end graphics cards have power demands that exceed AGP or PCIe slot capabilities.
[src:atx/atx] For these cards, supplementary power was delivered through a standard 4-pin peripheral or floppy power connector.
[src:atx/atx] Midrange and high-end PCIe graphics cards manufactured after 2004 typically use a standard 6- or 8-pin PCIe power connector directly from the PSU.
[src:atx/atx] Efficiency in power supplies means the extent to which power is not wasted in converting electricity from a household supply to regulated DC.
[src:atx/atx] Computer power supplies vary from around 70% to over 90% efficiency.
[src:atx/atx] Various initiatives exist to improve the efficiency of computer power supplies.
[src:atx/atx] Climate Savers Computing Initiative promotes energy saving and reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by encouraging development and use of more efficient power supplies.
[src:atx/atx] 80 PLUS certifies a variety of efficiency levels for power supplies and encourages their use via financial incentives.
[src:atx/atx] Efficient power supplies also save money by wasting less power; as a result they use less electricity to power the same computer, and they emit less waste heat which results in significant energy savings on central air conditioning in the summer.
[src:atx/atx] The gains of using an efficient power supply are more substantial in computers that use a lot of power.
[src:atx/atx] Although a power supply with a larger than needed power rating will have an extra margin of safety against overloading, such a unit is often less efficient and wastes more electricity at lower loads than a more appropriately sized unit.
[src:atx/atx] Thus, for a 100 W load, losses for this supply would be 27 W; if the same power supply was put under a 450 W load, for which the supply's efficiency peaks at 89%, the loss would be only 56 W despite supplying 4.5 times the useful power.
[src:atx/atx] For a comparison, a 500-watt power supply carrying the 80 Plus Bronze efficiency rating (which means that such a power supply is designed to be at least 82-percent efficient for loads above 100 W) may provide an 84 percent efficiency for a 100 W load, wasting only 19 W.
